1
00:00:00,950 --> 00:00:01,810
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:02,370 --> 00:00:06,750
In this video I'll show how to make a pyrotechnic product for the New Year holidays.

3
00:00:07,470 --> 00:00:10,510
Similar to the ones sold in stores.

4
00:00:11,190 --> 00:00:12,270
We'll be making rockets.

5
00:00:12,850 --> 00:00:15,750
For which we'll need three main ingredients.

6
00:00:16,310 --> 00:00:18,710
The first is potassium nitrate.

7
00:00:19,570 --> 00:00:25,830
It can be bought as crushed white crystals.

8
00:00:26,370 --> 00:00:29,690
Potassium nitrate can be picked up at plant supply stores.

9
00:00:30,350 --> 00:00:31,330
For plant protection.

10
00:00:31,910 --> 00:00:37,270
Or at stores selling fertilizers.

11
00:00:37,950 --> 00:00:44,330
In this case, a half-kilogram package was bought.

12
00:00:44,750 --> 00:00:46,830
The Buyskie Fertilizers brand.

13
00:00:47,730 --> 00:00:53,090
Or you can buy it in smaller 25-gram packets.

14
00:00:54,110 --> 00:00:57,530
The next main ingredient is sorbitol.

15
00:00:57,530 --> 00:01:05,590
It also comes as soft white crystals.

16
00:01:05,750 --> 00:01:11,410
Sorbitol is a substance that replaces sugar for diabetics.

17
00:01:11,570 --> 00:01:15,790
You buy it at pharmacies.

18
00:01:17,250 --> 00:01:21,650
Usually sold by weight in half-kilo portions.

19
00:01:23,450 --> 00:01:28,310
That much is enough for plenty of experiments.

20
00:01:28,810 --> 00:01:32,970
And the third ingredient is sulfur.

21
00:01:33,830 --> 00:01:38,550
In nature it occurs as bright yellow crystals.

22
00:01:39,150 --> 00:01:45,310
We buy it as a crushed yellow powder.

23
00:01:46,870 --> 00:01:49,930
Sulfur is sold at pet supply stores.

24
00:01:49,930 --> 00:01:52,510
At veterinary stores.

25
00:01:53,570 --> 00:01:58,570
Sold as an additive to livestock or bird feed.

26
00:01:59,490 --> 00:02:01,910
In this case, this kind of packaging.

27
00:02:02,510 --> 00:02:06,930
Check the description so that the sulfur is pure, without impurities.

28
00:02:08,150 --> 00:02:11,990
Or you can find it in this kind of packaging.

29
00:02:13,910 --> 00:02:19,390
Next, once you have these substances.

30
00:02:20,510 --> 00:02:23,450
Check how dry the substances are.

31
00:02:24,250 --> 00:02:27,030
Visually, they shouldn't look damp.

32
00:02:28,370 --> 00:02:33,590
If needed, the powders should be additionally dried on a radiator.

33
00:02:34,590 --> 00:02:44,530
After drying our three components, you might need to grind the potassium nitrate and sulfur further.

34
00:02:44,770 --> 00:02:53,870
If a component was previously moist and the moisture evaporated, lumps may form.

35
00:02:54,690 --> 00:03:02,810
We crush those lumps with a wooden object until a uniform powder forms.

36
00:03:03,890 --> 00:03:19,590
You don't need to do this with sorbitol, because in rocket fuel preparation the sorbitol melts into a fluid mass and the other components get added to it.

37
00:03:21,950 --> 00:03:27,090
After grinding the substances, we move to weighing them.

38
00:03:27,090 --> 00:03:37,130
For this we'll need household scales that can weigh substances to tenths of a gram.

39
00:03:37,230 --> 00:03:47,910
In this case I'm using scales that can accurately weigh up to 200 grams and read to hundredths.

40
00:03:47,950 --> 00:03:50,350
That suits us well.

41
00:03:50,350 --> 00:04:04,330
With the scales we measure out our components in a ratio of 60 grams potassium nitrate, 30 grams sorbitol, and 10 grams sulfur.

42
00:04:04,330 --> 00:04:21,330
That much mixed substance is enough later to fill two rocket motors like these to working capacity.

43
00:04:22,650 --> 00:04:30,430
Next we move to a critical step — making the rocket motor body.

44
00:04:30,430 --> 00:04:39,550
How you make it determines the flight characteristics of your pyrotechnic product.

45
00:04:39,970 --> 00:05:01,450
To make the body we'll need a plastic mandrel from water pipe with a 20 mm outer diameter, a 2.5 mm drill bit, a polished-surface metal object — in this case a 10 cm piece of old screwdriver.

46
00:05:01,450 --> 00:05:07,590
Long.

47
00:05:09,570 --> 00:05:20,210
And under the outer diameter of this metal pin, a drill bit is picked — in this case 4 mm outer diameter.

48
00:05:22,550 --> 00:05:34,330
The body material is A4 paper. To make one blank we'll need 8 sheets.

49
00:05:34,990 --> 00:05:47,890
Wind the paper onto the plastic mandrel — line up the paper ends and do one full wrap.

50
00:05:47,890 --> 00:06:00,390
After the first full wrap — pay attention — it's done without glue, otherwise it'll be very hard to extract the guide mandrel.

51
00:06:00,390 --> 00:06:19,330
After that, we smear the remaining surface of the sheet with PVA glue using a brush. Before all this, lay down oilcloth or polyethylene so you don't get glue on the workbench.

52
00:06:19,330 --> 00:06:21,490
On the workbench surface.

53
00:06:21,490 --> 00:06:50,950
Wind the paper this way — 8 layers, smearing each one with glue. Once you have a paper tube, extract the body from the mandrel and form a star pattern from paper at one end.

54
00:06:52,310 --> 00:07:09,430
This way, with 8 layers, the paper will be much thicker, but because it's glue-impregnated, it'll also be pliable. Then the star rays get folded over each other in a circle and compressed.

55
00:07:09,430 --> 00:07:10,270
Compressed.

56
00:07:10,270 --> 00:07:15,330
And once you've folded it, the whole thing gets wrapped with thread.

57
00:07:15,870 --> 00:07:22,430
Do the same thing on the opposite side — fold and wrap.

58
00:07:22,430 --> 00:07:26,870
You'll end up with a blank like this.

59
00:07:28,630 --> 00:07:40,430
Once we've wrapped it with thread, smear it all with PVA glue, impregnate each side well, and you get a blank.

60
00:07:40,510 --> 00:07:47,810
After drying, the blank gets cut with a utility knife into two halves.

61
00:07:47,810 --> 00:07:52,210
You can see we get two bodies from one blank.

62
00:07:53,650 --> 00:08:02,170
Drying is done on a radiator or directly on the heating boiler for at least 12 hours.

63
00:08:02,170 --> 00:08:11,190
After the glue dries, the whole blank gets rigid.

64
00:08:11,810 --> 00:08:19,750
If you knock on it, it sounds like a metal object hitting bone.

65
00:08:19,750 --> 00:08:25,330
The body acquires rigidity and strength.

66
00:08:25,970 --> 00:08:30,950
Now we weigh the body without rocket fuel.

67
00:08:33,570 --> 00:08:43,130
The body weight in this case is 16 grams.

68
00:08:54,290 --> 00:09:14,910
Once the blank is divided into two bodies, we move on to drilling the hole for gas exit that'll lift our pyrotechnic product.

69
00:09:14,910 --> 00:09:20,650
Into the sky — this hole is called the nozzle.

70
00:09:22,110 --> 00:09:40,930
For which we need a drill — with a thinner drill we drill the hole strictly vertically in the center, then widen it with a drill matching the outer diameter of the rod.

71
00:09:40,930 --> 00:09:45,610
Next we prepare the body for fuel pouring.

72
00:09:45,830 --> 00:09:48,910
A rod is inserted into the drilled hole.

73
00:09:49,850 --> 00:09:52,730
The rod should fit tightly — no wobble.

74
00:09:54,390 --> 00:10:03,410
And you can see that after insertion the rod sits in the center of the rocket motor body.

75
00:10:04,410 --> 00:10:15,570
You can also note that the rod height is set so we have about a centimeter and a half left to the edge of the motor body.

76
00:10:16,750 --> 00:10:24,510
The rod height determines the level the fuel is poured to in the rocket motor.

77
00:10:25,210 --> 00:10:28,390
That centimeter and a half will be sealed up later.

78
00:10:29,650 --> 00:10:32,230
On to fuel preparation.

79
00:10:32,370 --> 00:10:38,970
Cooking is better on an electric stove, but if you don't have one, cook on minimum flame.

80
00:10:39,810 --> 00:10:44,870
And with a metal object — in this case using a heat diffuser.

81
00:10:45,670 --> 00:11:01,470
First, the nitrate poured into a ceramic or metal container needs to be well heated for 4–5 minutes so the whole container and the powder inside are hot.

82
00:11:01,970 --> 00:11:07,130
If you don't do that, then later when you add the nitrate the fuel will thicken quickly.

83
00:11:08,130 --> 00:11:10,810
Heat the nitrate, then set it aside.

84
00:11:11,950 --> 00:11:21,330
Then take a metal cup — could be a metal cup, jar, whatever you have on hand.

85
00:11:22,270 --> 00:11:25,090
And pour pure sorbitol into it.

86
00:11:26,090 --> 00:11:29,110
The sorbitol needs to be brought to melting.

87
00:11:30,110 --> 00:11:37,670
Set up, now you can turn on the flame and bring the sorbitol to melting.

88
00:11:39,410 --> 00:11:44,710
After 5 minutes of heating, turn off the high flame.

89
00:11:46,250 --> 00:11:49,910
You can see the sorbitol has melted.

90
00:11:51,710 --> 00:11:54,790
A white mass forms.

91
00:11:56,950 --> 00:12:04,770
Continue melting with stirring until all particles are fully dissolved.

92
00:12:08,810 --> 00:12:11,910
A liquid mass forms.

93
00:12:17,930 --> 00:12:28,450
Now when it's fully melted, we move to pouring the nitrate into the sorbitol melt.

94
00:12:29,450 --> 00:12:32,610
The nitrate is already heated.

95
00:12:40,790 --> 00:12:48,210
Pour the nitrate, distribute it evenly over the surface.

96
00:12:49,450 --> 00:12:58,050
And after some heating on low flame, do the stirring.

97
00:13:08,680 --> 00:13:29,360
For those cooking for the first time, I recommend keeping a water container nearby so if it ignites, you can quickly lower the fuel container into the water.

98
00:13:32,140 --> 00:13:41,380
A white mass forms — uniform, like semolina porridge.

99
00:13:51,350 --> 00:14:04,970
Mix well, and only once you have a uniform mass do you add the sulfur, because sulfur causes the fuel to thicken.

100
00:14:05,150 --> 00:14:11,090
Add it to the mix at the very last.

101
00:14:12,830 --> 00:14:16,970
Distribute the sulfur and stir.

102
00:14:34,310 --> 00:14:47,350
The flame keeps burning at minimum, keeping our container warm.

103
00:14:49,730 --> 00:14:56,350
A uniform homogeneous mass forms, like this — now yellow-colored.

104
00:14:57,250 --> 00:14:58,670
That's it — fuel is ready.

105
00:14:59,670 --> 00:15:12,490
After this you can turn off the flame completely, and it's time to pour the fuel into the rocket motor.

106
00:15:13,410 --> 00:15:21,770
Find a convenient stand, the rod is centered, and we start pouring.

107
00:15:35,560 --> 00:15:40,960
The fuel is hot so it flows easily.

108
00:16:27,640 --> 00:16:30,020
Motor fully filled.

109
00:16:36,900 --> 00:16:51,020
Lightly tap on its walls and the fuel settles evenly inside the body.

110
00:17:05,170 --> 00:17:12,790
While the fuel cools in the rocket motor body, it shrinks a bit.

111
00:17:13,610 --> 00:17:17,750
You can see the central metal rod in there.

112
00:17:17,750 --> 00:17:26,790
For about 5 minutes, as we tap the body, the fuel thickens.

113
00:17:26,910 --> 00:17:29,890
You can see the rod is still slightly mobile.

114
00:17:31,110 --> 00:17:42,050
It'll take about 5–10 more minutes for the fuel to reach the needed consistency and then the inner pin can be removed.

115
00:17:42,050 --> 00:17:57,590
While the fuel is hardening in the first body, periodically reheat the remaining fuel on low flame and stir it so it doesn't thicken.

116
00:18:00,250 --> 00:18:15,650
You can see it's getting thicker, so it needs to be periodically reheated and then poured into the next prepared body.

117
00:18:32,880 --> 00:18:40,960
The fuel temperature needs to stay where the sulfur doesn't go into a molten state.

118
00:18:41,100 --> 00:18:46,680
That is, it should stay as a fine dispersion of powder in the fuel mixture.

119
00:18:47,200 --> 00:18:50,300
This is important for its characteristics.

120
00:18:50,780 --> 00:18:59,860
And in this fuel mixture, for more colorful effects, you can also add powders of various metals.

121
00:18:59,860 --> 00:19:08,740
For example, if you add a few grams of magnesium to the mix, there'll be a silver-white tail behind the rocket.

122
00:19:08,800 --> 00:19:13,640
Aluminum will give the same color, copper will add a greenish color.

123
00:19:14,060 --> 00:19:23,340
That is, you can experiment with this and find an effect that you like.

124
00:19:23,340 --> 00:19:35,180
We've reheated the fuel back to its initial state — now it can be poured into the second motor body too.

125
00:19:35,800 --> 00:19:44,960
The mix has thickened up nicely — now we can move to removing the rod from the body.

126
00:19:46,900 --> 00:19:51,960
Pull it out carefully — the rod will come out with some resistance.

127
00:19:59,180 --> 00:20:02,820
For this it should be polished.

128
00:20:10,720 --> 00:20:16,620
Did the extraction and we have a channel formed in the center.

129
00:20:17,040 --> 00:20:21,220
Here's an example of how this fuel burns in open air.

130
00:20:45,670 --> 00:21:04,470
Rocket fuel based on the recipe given at the start of the video, with sulfur added, has one distinctive feature compared to rocket fuel without sulfur.

131
00:21:05,970 --> 00:21:20,470
Plain rocket fuel — 60 g potassium nitrate and 40 g sorbitol — takes a long time to harden, about a day.

132
00:21:21,770 --> 00:21:30,450
Plus it doesn't have the mechanical properties of the fuel with sulfur added.

133
00:21:30,450 --> 00:21:41,210
Sulfur also takes part in the rocket fuel's burning, producing more gas.

134
00:21:41,450 --> 00:21:46,590
And sulfur strengthens the fuel itself.

135
00:21:47,070 --> 00:21:51,150
It transforms into a stone-like structure.

136
00:21:52,210 --> 00:22:06,870
You can hear it when you knock a metal object against it — and pretty hard. The fuel doesn't crack, no cracks form. That is, good mechanical properties.

137
00:22:07,290 --> 00:22:23,330
This is very important so that in the body where the fuel is poured there are no voids, because voids or fuel cracking during motor operation can lead to anomalous burning and the body bursting.

138
00:22:23,330 --> 00:22:27,290
And the body bursting.

139
00:22:28,010 --> 00:22:33,050
We don't want that, so we follow the manufacturing process.

140
00:22:34,050 --> 00:22:42,470
Fuel with sulfur added hardens in 10 hours to this state.

141
00:22:42,470 --> 00:22:49,730
After 10 hours, the motor is ready for use.

142
00:22:51,490 --> 00:22:55,710
You can mount it on the pyrotechnic product.

143
00:22:55,790 --> 00:23:02,970
During the build, a question may come up — why a central channel is formed in the rocket motor fuel.

144
00:23:02,970 --> 00:23:07,030
Let's analyze that with this drawing.

145
00:23:07,570 --> 00:23:10,190
Schematically — the motor in cross-section.

146
00:23:10,410 --> 00:23:16,890
These are the paper walls, the paper plug, and you can see the fuel with the central channel.

147
00:23:17,250 --> 00:23:18,710
Let's analyze the burning process.

148
00:23:18,850 --> 00:23:24,970
When the fuel is ignited, it burns along the entire length of the central channel.

149
00:23:24,970 --> 00:23:36,890
During burning, the diameter of the central channel keeps growing, and the fuel burns outward toward the walls while gas exits through the nozzle.

150
00:23:37,350 --> 00:23:48,930
This way we get a large diameter of burning fuel surface, fast burning, and as a result, big exhaust gas pressure.

151
00:23:49,410 --> 00:23:54,790
That way our pyrotechnic product gains very high speed.

152
00:23:54,970 --> 00:24:06,350
Able to climb much higher compared to a motor filled with fuel without a central channel.

153
00:24:07,790 --> 00:24:26,630
A second advantage of this design is that the burning fuel in the central channel protects the motor body walls from burning temperature and also from the exhaust gas pressure.

154
00:24:26,630 --> 00:24:27,110
Pressure.

155
00:24:27,650 --> 00:24:33,150
So the main working zone for us is the rocket motor nozzle.

156
00:24:33,150 --> 00:24:41,520
So the rocket motor nozzle has big requirements in terms of construction.

157
00:24:42,010 --> 00:24:45,610
It should be very well glued and wrapped with thread.

158
00:24:45,850 --> 00:24:49,410
This is the main part of the rocket motor.

159
00:24:49,890 --> 00:24:54,270
Let me show a motor that worked properly.

160
00:24:55,530 --> 00:24:59,430
I managed to find our prototype.

161
00:25:00,430 --> 00:25:02,930
You can see it was in operation.

162
00:25:04,690 --> 00:25:07,810
And you can pay attention to the nozzle.

163
00:25:08,130 --> 00:25:15,590
You can see the shape hasn't changed, the nozzle isn't torn, the thread is intact.

164
00:25:16,270 --> 00:25:21,570
Small burn zone during operation.

165
00:25:23,330 --> 00:25:31,810
The walls also stayed solid — they don't push in by hand pressure.

166
00:25:32,570 --> 00:25:38,670
That is, the motor ran stably without compromising the integrity of its build.

167
00:25:40,930 --> 00:25:50,190
Now I'll show an example of a motor that was in operation but didn't have a central channel formed.

168
00:25:51,530 --> 00:25:57,890
This motor was filled with fuel up to this point.

169
00:25:58,370 --> 00:26:01,650
And you can see what happened to the nozzle.

170
00:26:02,270 --> 00:26:06,630
Thread burned, there are burns in several spots.

171
00:26:09,330 --> 00:26:13,670
And the nozzle itself is torn from the gas pressure.

172
00:26:14,330 --> 00:26:24,990
You can see the tube crumples easily, meaning the walls thinned significantly during rocket fuel burning.

173
00:26:26,750 --> 00:26:40,010
After this demonstration I'll show video of how the launch of this pyrotechnic product went and what it led to.

174
00:26:43,830 --> 00:26:48,080
Moving on to forming the rocket motor plug.

175
00:26:48,950 --> 00:26:57,130
This part has special requirements since it takes huge pressure from the exhaust gases.

176
00:26:58,070 --> 00:27:12,310
And the pressure is such that if your plug is badly made, it'll just get knocked out and the rocket either won't fly at all or only to a tiny height.

177
00:27:12,310 --> 00:27:20,130
This part is critical, so it needs to be solidly fixed to the body.

178
00:27:20,630 --> 00:27:40,730
For the plug to glue to the body well, we need to remove the first layer of paper that wasn't impregnated with glue when we rolled the body on the plastic tube mandrel.

179
00:27:41,730 --> 00:27:51,550
This layer of paper is removed and folded over the surface of the fuel itself.

180
00:27:52,410 --> 00:28:01,890
This layer protects the channel in the rocket motor fuel from glue getting in.

181
00:28:02,620 --> 00:28:18,400
We scrape it off and tuck it down on the fuel surface, down to the well-glued layer.

182
00:28:18,830 --> 00:28:31,250
You have to do this, otherwise the poorly-attached paper might just get torn off by gas pressure.

183
00:28:31,890 --> 00:28:35,150
I'll show this together with the plug.

184
00:28:35,190 --> 00:28:42,890
A short video where you can clearly see the moment when the plug is badly made.

185
00:28:55,450 --> 00:29:06,750
Paper well pressed, a hole made to about 3 mm depth, after which the fuse goes into the hole.

186
00:29:06,750 --> 00:29:22,210
This way we set the fuse ignition time at the moment when the fuel has burned mostly through and the burning has reached the walls.

187
00:29:22,710 --> 00:29:25,570
After that, the fuse ignites.

188
00:29:26,430 --> 00:29:35,250
It burns for a second and a half, passing through the plug, after which it ignites the ejection charge.

189
00:29:35,250 --> 00:29:45,990
To form the plug body, we'll need porous fabric — medical bandage works well — and water-based glue.

190
00:29:47,750 --> 00:29:57,530
To start, generously smear glue on the walls and the rocket motor fuel surface.

191
00:29:57,530 --> 00:30:00,150
For

192
00:30:06,320 --> 00:30:09,060
this use a wooden stick.

193
00:30:41,340 --> 00:30:52,960
You need to smear the whole surface very well so the bandage gets impregnated and glued solidly.

194
00:30:52,960 --> 00:30:55,640
Bandage

195
00:31:09,680 --> 00:31:20,440
cut into strips about 10 cm and pressed into the body.

196
00:31:50,700 --> 00:32:01,980
Next the material should be packed in well, with the fuse itself pressed against the body wall.

197
00:32:26,620 --> 00:32:32,280
Then the first layer gets impregnated across the surface.

198
00:32:56,290 --> 00:33:05,150
Impregnate it really well so the whole fabric is full of glue.

199
00:33:07,050 --> 00:33:15,430
This gives a solid bond and adhesion of the surface to the rocket motor body.

200
00:33:54,250 --> 00:33:58,630
The fuse for ignition should be thicker.

201
00:33:58,770 --> 00:34:07,750
If the fuse from a pyrotechnic product is thin, better lay 2–3 of them in a bundle.

202
00:34:11,410 --> 00:34:14,850
First layer well impregnated.

203
00:34:15,790 --> 00:34:17,510
Add the second bandage layer.

204
00:34:52,400 --> 00:34:57,660
After adding the second layer we do an interesting step.

205
00:34:59,700 --> 00:35:05,000
We start forming stitching with the help of wire or thread.

206
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:14,540
For this, at the depth of the second layer surface, we make holes with an awl.

207
00:35:17,060 --> 00:35:29,200
Next we mark out a circle along which the stitching will go.

208
00:35:34,500 --> 00:35:42,060
Along the perimeter, holes are made every 8 mm or so.

209
00:36:35,640 --> 00:36:38,780
Now we move to stitching with wire.

210
00:36:39,780 --> 00:36:50,040
The wire is pulled through the hole and laid with crossings in the center.

211
00:36:50,420 --> 00:36:59,520
Pass to the next hole, then transition to the opposite hole.

212
00:36:59,520 --> 00:37:08,900
This way we form a mesh that tightly presses the first two layers of fabric against the fuel.

213
00:37:09,180 --> 00:37:14,580
After the glue hardens, you'll have a solid plug.

214
00:37:15,300 --> 00:37:26,120
Next we'll add another layer of glue-impregnated material and a final layer with the paper plug.

215
00:37:26,120 --> 00:37:31,640
After stitching, you get this kind of wire surface.

216
00:37:32,360 --> 00:37:37,840
It's actually more convenient to stitch with thread and a needle through these holes — it's faster.

217
00:37:37,940 --> 00:37:42,560
I used wire for clarity, so you can see how it's formed.

218
00:37:43,400 --> 00:37:48,260
Next we impregnate the surface with glue again.

219
00:37:55,040 --> 00:38:09,720
Solid gluing here is critical — so your plug doesn't get knocked out during operation, or burned through.

220
00:38:37,200 --> 00:38:49,260
One more bandage layer is added, after which we glue on porous paper.

221
00:38:49,920 --> 00:38:51,220
You can use a napkin.

222
00:38:52,100 --> 00:39:05,060
The last hole is closed and a flat surface is formed flush with the motor body.

223
00:39:05,060 --> 00:39:17,580
Before laying the paper, the layer is fully soaked in glue and fully impregnated.

224
00:39:18,020 --> 00:39:23,420
Then the paper goes onto this glue.

225
00:39:29,600 --> 00:39:40,160
For strength you can add fine sawdust here, or add gypsum.

226
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:52,900
Mixed with the glue, it'll increase strength and reduce the glue's drying time.

227
00:39:54,760 --> 00:40:03,740
In practice you can experiment and find the best builds for your own approach.

228
00:40:04,690 --> 00:40:16,260
Once the plug is fully dry, we move to forming the part that's responsible for the light and sound effects in the sky.

229
00:40:16,700 --> 00:40:21,420
For this we need to make paper tubes of various diameters.

230
00:40:21,600 --> 00:40:26,540
A diameter much larger than the rocket motor itself is fine.

231
00:40:26,960 --> 00:40:29,800
It all depends what you want to fill it with.

232
00:40:29,800 --> 00:40:34,060
In this case I took a body offcut.

233
00:40:35,120 --> 00:40:36,380
Now we fix it.

234
00:40:36,740 --> 00:40:44,280
You can see the fuse comes out to ignite the working substance.

235
00:40:46,040 --> 00:40:49,580
We fix it to the body with masking tape.

236
00:41:17,760 --> 00:41:21,140
What can be used as filling?

237
00:41:22,040 --> 00:41:25,440
Pretty much anything works as filling.

238
00:41:25,720 --> 00:41:33,240
Any cheap pyrotechnic products that can burn with sparkling stars.

239
00:41:35,620 --> 00:41:43,060
You can use those balls with sparkling stars — the filling from them.

240
00:41:43,060 --> 00:41:48,320
You can load some firecrackers in here.

241
00:41:49,520 --> 00:41:56,940
If you have a larger-diameter tube, you can fit a lot more firecrackers in there.

242
00:41:57,780 --> 00:42:03,360
I'm using this as an example of what you can do.

243
00:42:04,980 --> 00:42:10,980
Now — what serves as the ejection charge for this build?

244
00:42:11,900 --> 00:42:16,700
I use homemade black powder, for instance.

245
00:42:18,280 --> 00:42:23,380
But you can also use filling from pyrotechnic products.

246
00:42:23,940 --> 00:42:29,980
You can use granules of the same rocket fuel as the ejection charge.

247
00:42:29,980 --> 00:42:35,940
The granules are rolled into small 3–4 mm balls and you fill about 1 cm.

248
00:42:36,800 --> 00:42:45,500
In this case I'll fill the working zone with black powder.

249
00:42:53,640 --> 00:42:58,880
About 1 cm is enough for reliable ejection charge operation.

250
00:43:03,780 --> 00:43:10,100
For spectacle and effect, add metal powders.

251
00:43:11,040 --> 00:43:18,440
In this case I'll add some magnesium powder.

252
00:43:18,440 --> 00:43:20,920
Now

253
00:43:32,850 --> 00:43:37,010
the mix should be gently stirred.

254
00:43:43,240 --> 00:43:58,060
Magnesium will give a beautiful silver-white flash in the sky, visible while watching

255
00:44:01,150 --> 00:44:01,810
the mixture.

256
00:44:01,810 --> 00:44:12,990
Now we can move to installing the components that'll be ejected by gas pressure and work in the air.

257
00:44:13,050 --> 00:44:17,850
In this case I'll use firecrackers.

258
00:44:25,390 --> 00:44:29,410
Then load with sparkling stars.

259
00:44:29,790 --> 00:44:37,610
The whole filling should freely come out from the ejection charge pressure.

260
00:44:39,330 --> 00:44:42,310
It drops in without effort.

261
00:44:42,630 --> 00:44:48,630
Also using sparkling stars from a pyrotechnic product.

262
00:44:49,850 --> 00:44:54,690
Plastic balls that rupture with a crack.

263
00:44:54,970 --> 00:44:56,690
Taking their filling.

264
00:44:58,690 --> 00:45:07,430
Add some powder for reliable ignition of this part of the filling.

265
00:45:08,430 --> 00:45:16,010
The tip of the fuse goes down into this zone.

266
00:45:17,290 --> 00:45:25,130
We'll use a part from a disassembled ball as the nose cone.

267
00:45:25,390 --> 00:45:27,290
It fits really well here.

268
00:45:28,290 --> 00:45:30,410
Like this.

269
00:45:31,450 --> 00:45:36,810
It becomes like a little cap and holds very tightly.

270
00:45:38,410 --> 00:45:41,190
Our demo product is ready.

271
00:45:42,750 --> 00:45:50,070
Now I'll attach it to a wooden stabilizer with masking tape.

272
00:45:50,070 --> 00:45:54,130
The wooden stabilizer is about 80 cm long.

273
00:45:55,950 --> 00:45:59,280
And we'll test its flight characteristics.

274
00:46:00,270 --> 00:46:01,670
The product in finished form.

275
00:46:03,150 --> 00:46:07,810
Attached to the wooden stabilizer with masking tape.

276
00:46:08,810 --> 00:46:21,290
You can see we need to align the rocket motor's channel center with the wooden guide.

277
00:46:21,830 --> 00:46:37,790
And as the fuse to light the rocket fuel, we'll use two factory fuses from cheap pyrotechnic products twisted together with thread.

278
00:46:39,350 --> 00:46:47,730
The fuse — so it's solidly fixed — is bent and inserted into the motor.

279
00:46:54,080 --> 00:46:57,540
Now we weigh our finished product.

280
00:47:09,990 --> 00:47:12,660
Weight is 96 grams.
